title: Tactile Immersion of Portable Game by Using Phantom Sensation to the Forearm
title_en: Tactile Immersion of Portable Game by Using Phantom Sensation to the Forearm
abstract: 本研究は前腕へのPhantom Sensation（PhS）を用いて携帯型ゲームに触覚的没入感を補助する手法を提案する研究である。提案手法は約100Hzの振動刺激でPhSを生成する小型・低コストの前腕提示プロトタイプを携帯機と連携して実装し、瞬間的な提示によりPhSの表現の弱さが目立ちにくい設計で携帯型ゲームでの位置情報提示を行ったことを報告する。
abstract_en: This study proposes using Phantom Sensation (PhS) on the forearm to augment tactile immersion for portable games. The proposed approach implemented a small, low-cost forearm prototype that generated PhS with approximately 100Hz vibration and delivered transient presentations integrated with a handheld game to convey position information.
positioning_summary: 本研究は前腕へのPhantom Sensation（PhS）を用いて携帯型ゲームの触覚没入を補助する研究として位置づけられている。 本研究はPhSが複数刺激の同時提示で生じる擬似触覚であり刺激間で位置や強度を制御できることを根拠に、携帯型ゲーム向けの小型・安価な位置提示手段のギャップを埋めることを目的にしている。
positioning_summary_en: This study is positioned as research that uses Phantom Sensation (PhS) on the forearm to augment tactile immersion for portable games. This study justifies the approach by noting that PhS arises from simultaneous multiple stimuli and allows control of stimulus location and intensity, aiming to fill the gap for small, low-cost position-presentation methods for handheld games.
purpose_summary: 本研究の目的はPhSの表現が粗いという制約を考慮しつつ、前腕へのPhSを補助振動として携帯型ゲームの没入感を高めることである。 本研究は携帯型ゲームプレイヤー向けに小型・低コストのデバイスで位置情報を提示することを狙いとして、前腕提示による実用性を検証することを目的にしている。
purpose_summary_en: The purpose of this study is to enhance immersion in portable games by using forearm PhS as an auxiliary vibration while accounting for PhS's coarse expressiveness. The study aims to verify the practicality of presenting position information with a small, low-cost device for handheld game players through forearm presentation.
method_summary: 本研究は携帯型ゲーム機と連携する前腕提示プロトタイプを実装してPhSイメージを提示する方式を採用した。 本研究は約100Hzの振動刺激でPhSを生成し、小型で低コストな実装を行い瞬間的な提示を用いて前腕で位置情報を伝達する仕組みを実験的に構築した。
method_summary_en: This study implemented a forearm presentation prototype that cooperates with a portable game console to present PhS imagery. This study experimentally constructed a mechanism that generated PhS using approximately 100Hz vibration, implemented it in a small, low-cost form, and used transient presentations to convey position information on the forearm.
evaluation_summary: 本研究は携帯型ゲームソフトを用いて14名の被験者によるユーザ評価を実施して効果を検証した。 本研究の評価では14名の参加者が前腕へのPhS提示で位置情報が伝達され携帯型ゲームの没入感に寄与することが示唆され、瞬間提示によりPhSの表現の弱さが目立ちにくかったという結果が報告された。
evaluation_summary_en: This study evaluated the approach with a user study involving 14 participants using a portable game application. The evaluation in this study showed that presenting PhS on the forearm conveyed position information and contributed to immersion for the 14 participants, and the results indicated that transient presentation reduced the perceptibility of PhS's weak expressiveness.

Title: Tactile Immersion of Portable Game by Using Phantom Sensation to the Forearm
Authors: Hiroshi Kato, Yuuki Hashimoto, Hiroyuki Kajimoto
Year: 2009
Abstract: This study proposes using Phantom Sensation (PhS) on the forearm to augment tactile immersion for portable games. The proposed approach implemented a small, low-cost forearm prototype that generated PhS with approximately 100Hz vibration and delivered transient presentations integrated with a handheld game to convey position information.
Positioning Summary: This study is positioned as research that uses Phantom Sensation (PhS) on the forearm to augment tactile immersion for portable games. This study justifies the approach by noting that PhS arises from simultaneous multiple stimuli and allows control of stimulus location and intensity, aiming to fill the gap for small, low-cost position-presentation methods for handheld games.
Purpose Summary: The purpose of this study is to enhance immersion in portable games by using forearm PhS as an auxiliary vibration while accounting for PhS's coarse expressiveness. The study aims to verify the practicality of presenting position information with a small, low-cost device for handheld game players through forearm presentation.
Method Summary: This study implemented a forearm presentation prototype that cooperates with a portable game console to present PhS imagery. This study experimentally constructed a mechanism that generated PhS using approximately 100Hz vibration, implemented it in a small, low-cost form, and used transient presentations to convey position information on the forearm.
Evaluation Summary: This study evaluated the approach with a user study involving 14 participants using a portable game application. The evaluation in this study showed that presenting PhS on the forearm conveyed position information and contributed to immersion for the 14 participants, and the results indicated that transient presentation reduced the perceptibility of PhS's weak expressiveness.
